controllers specialize the shared reconcile path
with formal runtime ownership.
service: distributeddatabase
slug: distributeddatabaseprivateendpoint
kind: DistributedDatabasePrivateEndpoint
archetype: generated-service-manager
status/finalizer: required /
retain-until-confirmed-delete
requeue: provisioning, updating, terminating
provider states: create CREATING; update
UPDATING; delete DELETING
follow-up: create=read-after-write;
update=read-after-write; delete=confirm-delete
supported drift: definedTags, description,
displayName, freeformTags (+1 more)
reject before mutate: force-new fields
compartmentId, subnetId
create-only fields: none
list lookup:
oci_distributeddatabase_distributed_database_private_endpoints
filters compartmentId, displayName; exact
compartmentId plus displayName list filters,
then reuse only a unique summary candidate;
lifecycleState is intentionally omitted from the
list request and the runtime rereads
GetDistributedDatabasePrivateEndpoint before
binding or status projection
conflicts: none
open gaps: none
Create and delete responses can carry
`opc-work-request-id` headers, but the published
runtime stays lifecycle-classified and uses
those IDs only as shared request breadcrumbs
instead of polling `GetWorkRequest`.
`ListDistributedDatabasePrivateEndpoints`
returns summary items that omit `privateIp`, so
every successful bind or write path rereads
`GetDistributedDatabasePrivateEndpoint` before
projecting steady-state status.
The package-local update builder preserves
explicit clear intent for `description`,
`nsgIds`, `freeformTags`, and `definedTags`
instead of letting generatedruntime drop
zero-value clears.
Delete keeps the finalizer until
`GetDistributedDatabasePrivateEndpoint` or list
fallback confirms `DELETED` or NotFound.
end note
